{"id":"1901.00860","submitter":"Tom\\'a\\v{s} Kroupa","authors":"Tom\\'a\\v{s} Kroupa","title":"On Decomposition of Solutions for Coalitional Games","comments":"Submitted","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A solution concept on a class of transferable utility coalitional games is a\nmultifunction satisfying given criteria of economic rationality. Every solution\nassociates a set of payoff allocations with a coalitional game. This general\ndefinition specializes to a number of well-known concepts such as the core,\nShapley value, nucleolus etc. In this note it is shown that in many cases a\nsolution factors through a set of games whose members can be viewed as\nelementary building blocks for the solution. Two factoring maps have a very\nsimply structure. The first decomposes a game into its elementary components\nand the second one combines the output of the first map into the respective\nsolution outcome. The decomposition is then studied mainly for certain\npolyhedral cones of zero-normalized games.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 3 Jan 2019 10:00:14 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 12 Oct 2020 12:09:00 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-10-13"}
